author: Josh Cheek
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Bump version to 3.2.0

SiB is now expected to work on Windows, huge shoutout to Avdi Grimm for getting that figured out!

I think 3.2.0 is fair, the API itself should pretty much be backwards compatible.
Note some changes that are more likely to be relevant to users:

* There is now a wiki, I moved most of the stuff in the readme over to the wiki.
* SiB now expects unicode everywhere (eg no matter what your environment variables say).
  I can't tell if this is a big change or not. I feel like it technically deserves to be
  a semver major bump, but I honestly don't think anyone is using it in a way that is
  incompatible with this, if you are, I'm happy to work with you to get something figured
  out, please see: https://github.com/JoshCheek/seeing_is_believing/wiki/Encodings
* Deprecated the `-K` flag (it still works, but it is now deprecated, you shouldn't use
  it going forward. If you do use it and there is an error, it will notify you to
  update your invocation, but its not spamming you when the lib is otherwise working).
* Added dependency on ChildProcess. I *think* this is okay according to SemVer.
  Not totally clear (I assume that bumping a major version of a dependency
  requires your lib to bump major versions, so maybe I'm wrong on this one)
* Added `exceptions` to the Result object and JSON api (note that the old `exception`
  still works the same/similarly as before -- it was a bit under specified, but the core
  behaviour of a falsy value or an exception is still in place, so users shouldn't
  see a change in behaviour (I think it emitted `false` instead of `nil`, but
  hopefully no one is depending on a falsy value so specific). Do note that it
  is better to use `exceptions` than `exception` as it is more correct:
  systems that can fork can emit multiple exceptions.
* The child process now talks to the parent process through a TCPSocket.
  It used to spawn the process with an additional file decriptor, but that was
  flaky on Windows. See https://github.com/JoshCheek/seeing_is_believing/pull/92

Also many more of the tests will now work on JRuby and Windows, the only tests that use fork
now are the tests that test fork. Since we aren't using fork, ichannel isn't helpful anymore,
so remove it from dev deps

Part of #94
Addresses a number of concerns from #92

author: Avdi Grimm
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Add windows support.

There are a lot of changes here. Some of the highlights:
- Replace the Process stdlib with the cross-platform childprocess gem (primarily for better process group support).
- Replace a UNIX-specific Rakefile shell callout to `which`
- Skip selected specs/features on windows (e.g. anything that uses fork)
- Adjust many filehandle modes and encodings.
- Note that this builds on the previous commit which replaces the eventstream pipe with a TCP socket.

For 2.0.0, it looks like Queue calls something in the stdlib Thread lib
which calls Thread.current, so when it\'s undefined, that messes is up.
So that feature just won't be available for that version.

author: Josh Cheek
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Add --ignore-unknown-flags to allow compatibility with multiple versions of SiB

* Add flag --ignore-unknown-flags
* Mention it in the help screen.
* Some rewording between "flag" and "options"... in general,
  my language seems to be confused about when to use which.

Code which integrates with SiB (e.g. editor integrations) have difficulty
supporting changing interfaces. This flag allows the integration to specify
that unknown options not be treated as errors (e.g. typos). This will allow
a situation such as:

```
SiB v100 has flags
  √ --flag1
  √ --flag2
  X --flag3

Sib v200 has flags
  X --flag1
  √ --flag2
  √ --flag3
```

Currently, the integration would have to check which version it is using
to determine which flags to set. Otherwise, this would happen:

```

$ seeing_is_believing _100_ --flag1 --flag2 --flag3
Error: --flag3 is not a flag, see the help screen (-h) for a list of options

$ seeing_is_believing _200_ --flag1 --flag2 --flag3
Error: --flag1 is not a flag, see the help screen (-h) for a list of options
```

Now, though, it can use the flag to tell each version to ignore the flags the don't know,
and thus call SiB with a set of flags that will be compatible across multiple versions:

```
$ seeing_is_believing _100_ --flag1 --flag2 --flag3 && echo $?
0

$ seeing_is_believing _200_ --flag1 --flag2 --flag3 && echo $?
0
```

Some flags got renamed, but I have to use the deprecated versions
(see features/deprecated-flags.feature) because they work on both
v2 and v3. Would be better to be able to specify to ignore the new flag,
and then set them both.

author: Josh Cheek
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Uhm... sigh, legit spent 3+ hours trying to get this to work.

SimpleCov has like 50 places you can enter it, all with some implicit
knowledge about the environment. It keeps overriding exit statuses,
but not in reliably reproducable ways (e.g. I run the suite, it blows up,
I run the one spec, it's fine). It calls Kernel.exit, overriding
the error that SiB needs to record. I tried to clean it up, but moving
one line to another in a way that should absolutely not matter, winds
up causing its tests to fail. This is because it stores all its sate
in singletons, so somehow something happening in the interim was going
and mutating it.

IDK, coverage API looks pretty simple, and SimpleCov breaks down as soon
as you deviate from its expectation, so if I really care about this, I'll
probably just write my own and see if I can't use their formatter for
inspecting it.

I will give it this, though: when I didn't shoot for 100% and thus
didn't try to get it to consolidate its result across processes, then it
didn't blow up, and the info I got from that was useful.

But srsly, kill off the singletons.

author: Josh Cheek
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Re-encode invalid EventStream messages (Fixes #46)

https://github.com/JoshCheek/seeing_is_believing/issues/46

Algorithm
---------

1. First transcode it to UTF8.
2. If that's not valid, force encode it to UTF8.
   Purpose of this is to try and "undo" encoding errors
   (a heuristic: "maybe they just fucked it up like the JSON lib")
3. But, at the end of the day, we need to be able to have valid strings,
   or they'll blow up on us in strange ways, so just replace
   anything that's still invalid with that funky question mark thing.

UTF-8
-----

Converting all strings to UTF8 because I don't know what the right encoding to use is.
There's like 50 encoding things I can look at, and I have no idea what's right.
Maybe if this affects you, let me know and we can figure it out.

Here are some possibilities:

* `__ENCODING__`
* `Encoding.default_internal`
* `Encoding.default_external`
* `$stdin.internal_encoding`
* `$stdin.external_encoding`
* `$stdout.internal_encoding`
* `$stdout.external_encoding`
* `"abc".encoding`
* `Encoding.find("locale")`

author: Josh Cheek
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Clean up cukes a bit more

* More normalizing whitespace
* Fixed some more overlapping filenames

A couple of different one-liners to do it:

```sh
$ ag 'Given the file' | ruby -ane '~/"(.*?)"/ and puts "#{$1.chomp} #{$F[0]}"' | sort | ruby -ane 'BEGIN{prev=[]}; prev[0]==$F[0] ? p(prev, $F) : prev=$F'
$ ag 'Given the file' | ruby -rpp -e '$stdin.readlines.group_by { |l| l[/".*?"/] }.map(&:last).each { |ls| puts ls, "\n" if ls.size > 1 }'
$ ag 'Given the file' | ruby -ane 'puts $_[/"(.*?)"/, 1]' | sort | uniq -d | xargs -I X ag 'Given the file .*?X'
```

author: Josh Cheek
description: Displays the results of every line of code in your file
Commit:
Pretty printed inspections are pulled up to AddAnnotation

This is a big advancement in terms of #44

Still needs to:
* Put them on multiple lines
* Select the correct widths (where does xmpfilter get this value?)
* Clean that shit up >.<
* Make sure that we can pass the result of one of these things back
  through and it'll get correctly cleaned up

Other notes:

* ExtractFindComments out of RewriteComments.
  I'm not really happy with this, anything that does a job should not be
  an object. Thinking about trying to pull the initialization of all
  these parser things up as high as possible, then they can parse
  just once and hand that stuff around, instead of every class that
  needs code parsed having to deal with this shit.
* Get some tests passing again (got more to do, but I need to work w/ my sister for a bit)

    r = Marshal.load(Open3.capture3("ruby -r seeing_is_believing -e 'puts Marshal.dump SeeingIsBelieving::Result.new.tap { |r| r.stdout = %.sout.; r.stderr=%.serr.'}").first)

The above will work if you don't set stderr, but does not work if you
do. No idea why, but going back to YAML to fix this. And since YAML
doesn't serialize the backtrace, explicitly serializing and re-setting
that.
